{"Title": "Stratified Abstraction of Access Control Policies", "Year": 2020, "Source": "Lect. Notes Comput. Sci.", "Volume": "12224 LNCS", "Issue": null, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": 165, "PageEnd": 176, "CitedBy": 1, "DOI": "10.1007/978-3-030-53288-8_9", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85089226412&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 2020, The Author(s).The shift to cloud-based APIs has made application security critically depend on understanding and reasoning about policies that regulate access to cloud resources. We present stratified predicate abstraction, a new approach that summarizes complex security policies into a compact set of positive and declarative statements that precisely state who has access to a resource. We have implemented stratified abstraction and deployed it as the engine powering AWS\u2019s IAM Access Analyzer service, and hence, demonstrate how formal methods and SMT can be used for security policy explanation.", "AuthorKeywords": null, "IndexKeywords": ["Access control policies", "Application security", "Cloud-based", "Compact sets", "New approaches", "Predicate abstractions", "Security policy"], "DocumentType": "Book Series", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 1, "EID": "2-s2.0-85089226412", "SubjectAreas": [["Theoretical Computer Science", "MATH", "2614"], ["Computer Science (all)", "COMP", "1700"]], "AuthorData": {"55871996100": {"Name": "Backes J.", "AuthorID": "55871996100", "AffiliationID": "60076757", "AffiliationName": "Amazon Web Services"}, "57218453703": {"Name": "Berrueco U.", "AuthorID": "57218453703", "AffiliationID": "60076757", "AffiliationName": "Amazon Web Services"}, "57218452217": {"Name": "Bray T.", "AuthorID": "57218452217", "AffiliationID": "60076757", "AffiliationName": "Amazon Web Services"}, "57218449385": {"Name": "Brim D.", "AuthorID": "57218449385", "AffiliationID": "60076757", "AffiliationName": "Amazon Web Services"}, "13008902100": {"Name": "Cook B.", "AuthorID": "